WEBVTT

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:01.120
My name is Michael Chow.

00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:04.120
I'm a software engineer at PositPBC,

00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:06.240
and I'm really excited to talk to you today

00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:09.780
about how documentation is cursed.

00:00:09.780 --> 00:00:12.220
And what I mean by that is I'm really interested

00:00:12.220 --> 00:00:15.520
in documentation for open source tools.

00:00:15.520 --> 00:00:17.600
And during this talk, I want you to think about

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:19.760
some of the documentation you've looked at

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:22.559
for different tools you've been interested in.

00:00:22.559 --> 00:00:25.879
Have you ever looked at a documentation site for a tool

00:00:25.879 --> 00:00:28.760
and felt like it's loaded up with information,

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:31.639
but it's not really the information you need?

00:00:31.639 --> 00:00:35.459
I'd say that documentation site is cursed.

00:00:35.459 --> 00:00:37.480
And I'm really excited, I think,

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:40.560
to really dive into what that means.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:43.759
I think we have to go back 2,500 years

00:00:43.759 --> 00:00:46.880
to the Greek myth of Tantalus,

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:50.080
who was cursed to be put under a tree

00:00:50.080 --> 00:00:53.599
where branches of fruit hung right above his head,

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:55.439
and there was water at his feet.

00:00:55.439 --> 00:00:57.900
But when he reached up to grab the fruit,

00:00:57.900 --> 00:01:00.020
it was blown beyond his grasp.

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:01.700
And when he went to drink the water,

00:01:01.700 --> 00:01:04.220
it receded so he couldn't reach it.

00:01:04.220 --> 00:01:08.220
So what he needed was forever at arm's length.

00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:10.720
And I think that cursed documentation

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:13.660
is worse than regular documentation

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:16.059
because it tantalizes users

00:01:16.059 --> 00:01:19.900
with the promise of the answers you need.

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:22.900
But ultimately, we often can't get the understanding

00:01:22.900 --> 00:01:26.980
that we need to do the problems to solve our problems.

00:01:26.980 --> 00:01:30.019
So you might see docs, but it might be really hard

00:01:30.019 --> 00:01:33.180
to figure out how everything fits together.

00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:34.220
And what I'll talk about today

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:37.379
is I think that in 99% of the cases,

00:01:37.379 --> 00:01:40.540
the solution is a really good user guide.

00:01:40.540 --> 00:01:44.779
So I wanna go into what a user guide is and does,

00:01:44.779 --> 00:01:47.660
and then five steps for creating a user guide.

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:50.820
All right, so to do that,

00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:53.339
I'm gonna use great tables as an example.

00:01:53.339 --> 00:01:54.459
And I'm glad Rich talked,

00:01:54.459 --> 00:01:56.699
so he showed off great tables a little bit.

00:01:57.660 --> 00:01:59.260
Great tables, it's really hard, I think,

00:01:59.260 --> 00:02:02.820
to solve this problem and to do a good user guide.

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:04.900
And so I just wanna flag what this looks like

00:02:04.900 --> 00:02:06.580
in great tables.

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:09.899
So great tables has two really recognizable pieces.

00:02:09.899 --> 00:02:11.779
It has this examples gallery,

00:02:11.779 --> 00:02:14.779
which is actually our most popular page on the site.

00:02:14.779 --> 00:02:17.339
And then it has this API reference,

00:02:17.339 --> 00:02:20.179
which is all the little pieces laid out.

00:02:21.419 --> 00:02:23.419
And then we, but I would say we probably spent

00:02:23.419 --> 00:02:27.300
the most time teasing out this piece, the user guide.

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:30.860
So to show what a user guide is and does,

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:33.139
let's go through the examples in reference

00:02:33.139 --> 00:02:36.619
as if those were the only documentation we had.

00:02:36.619 --> 00:02:38.300
So let's say you're looking at great tables

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:41.960
for the first time, and you pop open the examples page.

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:43.259
This is the most popular page

00:02:43.259 --> 00:02:46.940
because it shows you at a glance real life use cases.

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:49.539
It really highlights why you would use great tables

00:02:49.539 --> 00:02:52.580
and realistic things you could do with it.

00:02:52.580 --> 00:02:54.380
So you might pick out this table

00:02:54.380 --> 00:02:55.660
as a really interesting table.

00:02:55.660 --> 00:02:57.899
This is our coffee table,

00:02:57.899 --> 00:02:59.100
which represents the sales

00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:03.820
of a fictitious coffee equipment supplier.

00:03:03.820 --> 00:03:05.460
And so this shows off a lot of nice things

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:06.699
about great tables.

00:03:06.699 --> 00:03:10.339
It shows off some different elements,

00:03:10.339 --> 00:03:13.500
like making a title and filling backgrounds

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:15.860
and styling things like bolding stuff.

00:03:16.779 --> 00:03:19.119
So let's say you wanna take this and adapt it,

00:03:19.119 --> 00:03:21.380
and maybe you look at the code a little bit.

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:25.419
And to dig deeper, let's say you open the API reference.

00:03:25.419 --> 00:03:27.779
So you go there, you hit this page,

00:03:27.779 --> 00:03:30.899
and basically what the API reference is,

00:03:30.899 --> 00:03:34.860
is it's a big list of functions categorized a little bit,

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:37.419
and it has a lot of pages that just go into detail

00:03:37.419 --> 00:03:39.500
on all these tiny pieces.

00:03:39.500 --> 00:03:42.600
But what I'm showing here is not the full story.

00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:45.619
As it turns out, API references are pretty big.

00:03:45.619 --> 00:03:48.000
So even this isn't quite it.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.639
It's actually something more like this.

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:53.559
So you've got this neat example,

00:03:53.559 --> 00:03:56.059
and you've got 105 functions,

00:03:56.059 --> 00:03:59.619
and I think at this point you're a little bit cursed.

00:03:59.619 --> 00:04:01.639
You have a really nice example in your hand.

00:04:01.639 --> 00:04:04.039
You have 105 tiny things,

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:05.679
but I would say what you're missing

00:04:05.679 --> 00:04:09.320
is these sort of like middle-sized chunks,

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:13.339
the strategies to be able to break down examples

00:04:13.339 --> 00:04:15.360
into the tiny pieces,

00:04:15.360 --> 00:04:19.119
and know how to remix things for your problems.

00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:23.380
And that's exactly what a user guide does.

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:27.459
So I think that takes us to user guides.

00:04:27.459 --> 00:04:29.320
How can we break this curse?

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:32.059
If I have one really neat example in my hand,

00:04:32.059 --> 00:04:36.220
and the absolute deluge of 105 little tiny functions,

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:39.359
how can I find what I need?

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:43.720
So I think the key is that a user guide

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:47.079
can really help you understand the big structure

00:04:47.079 --> 00:04:51.119
of examples and the big pieces for your problems.

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:54.480
So for example, if we're onboarding you to this example,

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:58.440
we might flag that there's a key piece

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:01.260
which is structure in GreatTables.

00:05:01.260 --> 00:05:03.299
So that's something like this title

00:05:03.299 --> 00:05:06.760
and these column spanners, these high-level labels,

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:09.640
or the fact that you can kind of clean up column names.

00:05:09.640 --> 00:05:13.859
These are all structure activities in GreatTables.

00:05:13.859 --> 00:05:16.660
We might also point out there's formatting.

00:05:17.179 --> 00:05:20.100
So you can take these values

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:22.119
and you can turn them into currencies,

00:05:22.119 --> 00:05:24.619
or you can turn them into things like percentages.

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:27.140
We also might point out

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:29.899
that there's another activity called styling.

00:05:29.899 --> 00:05:32.220
You can color the background of a column,

00:05:32.220 --> 00:05:35.299
or you can bold a row of text.

00:05:35.299 --> 00:05:37.760
So the point here is that we've flagged

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:40.980
kind of three big activities you can use

00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:43.700
as sort of an in-between between the tiny chunks

00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:46.040
and the examples to help you understand

00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:49.739
the overall structure of GreatTables.

00:05:49.739 --> 00:05:53.459
And I'll call these components strategic components.

00:05:53.459 --> 00:05:55.760
These are these kind of like middle chunks.

00:05:57.339 --> 00:05:59.380
And I want to flag that this example,

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:01.959
I'll say this is a really good use of induction.

00:06:01.959 --> 00:06:05.339
We're using a case study or a concrete example

00:06:05.339 --> 00:06:08.260
to teach you about general ideas.

00:06:10.779 --> 00:06:12.019
The other thing I want to point out

00:06:12.019 --> 00:06:15.899
that's a challenge for user guides is task sequencing.

00:06:16.679 --> 00:06:19.559
So this is the table that we might onboard someone with,

00:06:19.559 --> 00:06:22.480
but I would say it's super hard to find,

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:25.480
even figure out like which example do we start with,

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:28.600
or how do we kind of weave through an example

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:30.679
to break it down for people.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:35.559
But I would say this is the crux of a user guide,

00:06:35.559 --> 00:06:37.920
is trying to get like a really good onboarding

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:40.760
so someone has an end-to-end example,

00:06:40.760 --> 00:06:42.980
and then being able to sort of,

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:46.200
instead of flag 105 functions,

00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:50.119
have say like 10 to 15 big concepts

00:06:50.119 --> 00:06:51.880
that you want people to know,

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:54.320
so that they have this kind of digestible way

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:55.500
to break stuff down.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:58.040
All right.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:01.899
So that's the crux of what a user guide is and does.

00:07:01.899 --> 00:07:04.000
It's those intermediate pieces

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.600
and the need to get a really nice onboarding.

00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:10.640
I think what I want to spend the rest of my time on

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:15.459
is five steps I think are important to breaking the curse,

00:07:15.459 --> 00:07:18.700
or how I would approach designing a user guide.

00:07:19.779 --> 00:07:22.100
So I find user guides really tricky.

00:07:22.100 --> 00:07:25.179
So working with Rich on Great Tables and Point Blank,

00:07:25.179 --> 00:07:26.820
one interesting thing was,

00:07:26.820 --> 00:07:29.859
Rich had worked a lot with these libraries,

00:07:29.859 --> 00:07:31.980
and I came in not really know,

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:33.760
I had no idea what they did.

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:35.299
And so what we had to do is,

00:07:35.299 --> 00:07:38.339
Rich just had to hit me with example after example,

00:07:38.339 --> 00:07:41.440
to kind of like beat me over the head with examples

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:45.100
until some idea of the pieces came out.

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:48.040
And so I'll say this five step process

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:50.559
sort of emerged from me trying to figure out

00:07:50.559 --> 00:07:53.559
how do we pull a user guide out of these libraries

00:07:53.559 --> 00:07:55.760
I had never used before.

00:07:55.760 --> 00:07:58.519
So I'll say the first step is collecting examples,

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:02.320
followed by scoping concepts,

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:05.279
so breaking the examples apart,

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:07.040
and then sequencing and onboarding,

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:09.899
figuring out how you would get a new person

00:08:09.899 --> 00:08:13.619
to understand the crux of what your library does.

00:08:13.619 --> 00:08:17.299
And then finally, detailing all the remaining concepts

00:08:17.299 --> 00:08:19.380
or the big pieces left over,

00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:20.920
and then drafting a workshop,

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:22.779
which I think is kind of like

00:08:22.779 --> 00:08:24.940
the documentation form of touching grass,

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:28.220
being sure that your documentation's meant for humans,

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:30.459
and you can see when they have a bad time,

00:08:30.459 --> 00:08:31.859
or a good time with it.

00:08:31.859 --> 00:08:33.140
I hope they have a good time.

00:08:33.140 --> 00:08:36.020
But usually they have a bad time when I run workshops.

00:08:37.260 --> 00:08:38.099
And just to flag,

00:08:38.099 --> 00:08:41.500
so I'm gonna summarize some techniques as I go through this

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:44.900
to, I think, really try to pull out a nice user guide.

00:08:46.299 --> 00:08:47.419
All right.

00:08:47.419 --> 00:08:49.979
So the first is collecting examples.

00:08:49.979 --> 00:08:53.419
I think the key here is to get the worst examples.

00:08:53.419 --> 00:08:56.219
It's W-R-S-T, which I would say is

00:08:56.219 --> 00:08:58.500
you want examples that are whole,

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:02.179
real world, simple, and typical.

00:09:02.179 --> 00:09:04.859
So you want a real, complete example

00:09:04.859 --> 00:09:06.479
that you might see in the wild

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:11.719
that's not too bananas to hit people with,

00:09:12.919 --> 00:09:16.200
that someone doing this type of thing might actually do.

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:17.840
So it's typical.

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:19.380
And I'm sure you've seen in docs,

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:21.580
one challenge is sometimes it has a lot of examples,

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:23.599
but they're little tiny pieces,

00:09:23.599 --> 00:09:25.440
and the pieces don't add up.

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:28.919
So I think that ensuring it's whole and real world

00:09:28.919 --> 00:09:32.320
makes sure that you're tackling real problems.

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:34.840
And simplicity is all about making sure

00:09:35.679 --> 00:09:37.979
that a newcomer can actually digest it.

00:09:37.979 --> 00:09:40.260
It's efficient for new learners.

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:44.820
So we settled on these three tables

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:46.919
as really reference points.

00:09:46.919 --> 00:09:49.539
And I think Rich showed this off in the last talk.

00:09:49.539 --> 00:09:53.179
So this is one he created on chemical compounds.

00:09:53.179 --> 00:09:55.619
So this is, Rich has a PhD in chemistry,

00:09:55.619 --> 00:09:58.460
so this is a table that's sort of real to him.

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:01.799
And this was useful to see some of the additional things

00:10:01.799 --> 00:10:03.840
you could do with great tables.

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:06.780
And then this one we pulled off social media

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:08.020
from Grant Chalmers.

00:10:09.739 --> 00:10:12.059
This is a carbon emissions table.

00:10:12.059 --> 00:10:14.179
And one neat thing is it's sort of like a blend

00:10:14.179 --> 00:10:16.099
between a table and a heat map.

00:10:16.099 --> 00:10:19.140
So it introduces some really interesting concepts.

00:10:19.140 --> 00:10:21.700
How can you create a heat map table

00:10:21.700 --> 00:10:24.820
and do things like make sure the columns are the same width

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:26.380
and some other nice things.

00:10:28.580 --> 00:10:31.979
And I will say we had really great inspiration.

00:10:31.979 --> 00:10:36.239
So we were lucky to have the 2024 Posit Table Contest

00:10:36.239 --> 00:10:37.080
to reference.

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:39.640
So Rich and another person named Curtis Kephart

00:10:39.640 --> 00:10:41.640
have run a contest for the last few years

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:46.099
to get people's neatest, worstiest examples.

00:10:46.099 --> 00:10:48.599
And this was really great inspiration to see

00:10:48.599 --> 00:10:50.960
what's the range of things people might do

00:10:50.960 --> 00:10:54.260
and sort of variation across real use cases.

00:10:56.080 --> 00:10:59.039
All right, so that's collecting examples

00:10:59.039 --> 00:11:01.020
and doing your worst.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:04.359
Next, I would say scoping concepts.

00:11:04.359 --> 00:11:06.299
So breaking them apart.

00:11:07.359 --> 00:11:09.559
All right, so I showed this.

00:11:09.559 --> 00:11:11.479
And the key here I just want to emphasize

00:11:11.479 --> 00:11:16.039
is that mapping concepts is so important.

00:11:16.039 --> 00:11:19.260
As Rich just produced example after example,

00:11:19.260 --> 00:11:22.440
I feel like we had them in whiteboarding software online

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:25.919
and we were just marking them up like crazy.

00:11:25.919 --> 00:11:29.460
When I show you this idea of structure, format and style,

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:30.880
this idea has caught on a bit.

00:11:30.880 --> 00:11:34.400
We've seen people use it when they're teaching workshops

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:37.520
and it's really been helpful for structuring our docs.

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:41.119
But I can't emphasize enough that when we started this task,

00:11:41.119 --> 00:11:43.760
we didn't know these were the concepts we'd use.

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:47.760
We actually had to do tons of diagramming and examples

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:51.099
to understand that we might actually use these concepts.

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:54.320
The other thing is Rich produced

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:55.919
this really great domain model.

00:11:55.919 --> 00:11:58.520
So he dove into this idea of table structure

00:11:58.520 --> 00:12:02.400
and he produced a diagram of all the different parts

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:04.599
that you might customize in a table,

00:12:04.599 --> 00:12:07.520
all the different individual pieces of table structure.

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:09.200
And I think this is a really neat way

00:12:09.200 --> 00:12:11.840
to emphasize core pieces of strategy

00:12:13.200 --> 00:12:15.440
and sort of bubble up like a cheat sheet

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:18.520
that people can reference and use to understand your tools.

00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:21.440
All right.

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:24.599
And all this adds up to for breaking the curse

00:12:24.599 --> 00:12:27.619
is filling in these missing pieces.

00:12:27.619 --> 00:12:30.340
So for us, structure, format, and style

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:34.059
are really nice things we can kind of like hang our hats on.

00:12:34.059 --> 00:12:36.820
They're just a good size for explaining things.

00:12:36.820 --> 00:12:38.900
You can pull up any example and ask

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:42.479
what are the structure, format, and style pieces.

00:12:42.479 --> 00:12:45.520
And we even organize our code using these concepts.

00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:48.539
All right.

00:12:48.539 --> 00:12:51.219
So that's the idea of getting the examples

00:12:51.219 --> 00:12:54.059
and breaking them apart into concepts.

00:12:54.059 --> 00:12:55.619
I would say once you're at this stage,

00:12:55.619 --> 00:12:58.219
you're in a good place to sequence in onboarding.

00:12:59.979 --> 00:13:02.780
And I won't go into detail into onboardings.

00:13:02.780 --> 00:13:05.099
And I will also note that actually immediately after this,

00:13:05.099 --> 00:13:07.880
I have a PR to open on Great Tables Docs

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:09.539
because I've cheated.

00:13:09.539 --> 00:13:12.419
As it turns out, library maintainers are not great

00:13:12.419 --> 00:13:15.219
with their docs all the time and that includes this guy.

00:13:16.260 --> 00:13:20.059
So I need to really flesh out the Great Tables onboarding.

00:13:20.059 --> 00:13:22.799
I feel like this talk was the inspiration I needed.

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:27.440
But I will emphasize onboarding's been really discussed

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:30.119
a lot and there are a lot of really nice examples

00:13:30.119 --> 00:13:31.739
you can find of it out there.

00:13:31.739 --> 00:13:36.280
So I'd say R for Data Science, the book R Packages,

00:13:36.280 --> 00:13:39.020
and Plot 9, another guide I've worked on,

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:41.359
all have really thorough onboardings

00:13:42.640 --> 00:13:44.239
that you can use and reference.

00:13:44.239 --> 00:13:45.320
I'm not gonna go into detail

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:49.039
because I think this topic is basically its own whole talk.

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:53.919
But in general, a lot of these really great user guides

00:13:53.919 --> 00:13:57.400
I've seen have emphasized this concept of the whole game.

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:01.799
So teach the whole kind of end-to-end picture

00:14:01.799 --> 00:14:04.599
so people have the big pieces

00:14:05.799 --> 00:14:09.119
and the kind of like sense for the big game

00:14:09.119 --> 00:14:11.679
before you go into the individual bits.

00:14:13.299 --> 00:14:16.159
All right, so I'm gonna kind of skip sequencing

00:14:16.159 --> 00:14:17.719
for the sake of time.

00:14:17.719 --> 00:14:19.679
But I would say the emphasis there

00:14:19.679 --> 00:14:21.640
is to ensure you do the whole game.

00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:25.580
So you take your favorite worstiest example

00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:28.039
and basically turn it into an onboarding.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:32.119
All right, so the last things

00:14:32.119 --> 00:14:35.000
are detailing the remaining concepts

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.159
and drafting a workshop.

00:14:37.159 --> 00:14:39.159
And I think detailing remaining concepts

00:14:39.159 --> 00:14:40.880
is one of my favorite topics

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:42.820
because I think most people

00:14:42.820 --> 00:14:45.179
can get to onboarding pretty quickly.

00:14:45.179 --> 00:14:47.000
But I feel like there's this kind of like

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.119
now what sense sometimes

00:14:49.119 --> 00:14:53.619
after you give people like their first onboarding piece.

00:14:54.760 --> 00:14:55.820
And I think what's neat,

00:14:55.820 --> 00:14:58.020
one neat approach technique I've used

00:14:58.020 --> 00:15:00.320
is this idea of a concept matrix.

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:02.760
But there are sort of like hidden concepts

00:15:02.760 --> 00:15:05.000
in your documentation.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:09.159
So what I do sometimes is I put the function names on rows

00:15:09.159 --> 00:15:10.799
and then I'll put different parameters

00:15:10.799 --> 00:15:13.159
things could take on columns.

00:15:13.159 --> 00:15:16.479
And this is just to emphasize shared structure

00:15:16.919 --> 00:15:18.159
across the package.

00:15:18.159 --> 00:15:21.239
So an API reference usually goes horizontal.

00:15:21.239 --> 00:15:24.760
It'll take one function and describe it in detail.

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:27.080
But what I like about the concept matrix

00:15:27.080 --> 00:15:31.580
is that I think it flags pieces in the guide

00:15:31.580 --> 00:15:33.719
where there should be guide pages.

00:15:33.719 --> 00:15:36.679
So I would say guide pages should be vertical.

00:15:36.679 --> 00:15:40.020
They should do slices that emphasize structure

00:15:40.020 --> 00:15:41.960
shared across functions

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:45.559
or pieces that you might not see in the docs.

00:15:45.559 --> 00:15:46.400
Uh-oh.

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:49.359
Whoa, see ya.

00:15:49.359 --> 00:15:50.320
Oh, we're back.

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:51.599
Okay.

00:15:51.599 --> 00:15:53.679
That was my, Max gave me a five minute warning.

00:15:53.679 --> 00:15:56.559
So maybe that was his big way.

00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:01.919
All right, so the concept matrix helps you

00:16:01.919 --> 00:16:04.900
by exposing these sort of like vertical slices.

00:16:06.299 --> 00:16:07.359
And the example I'd say here

00:16:07.359 --> 00:16:10.000
is we have a page on column selection.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.080
We noticed functions across categories,

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:13.919
structure, format, style.

00:16:13.919 --> 00:16:18.400
A lot of them can select columns of a table to work on.

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:21.599
And this actually involves a little bit of,

00:16:21.599 --> 00:16:23.039
there's quite a few options you can do

00:16:23.039 --> 00:16:24.760
for selecting columns.

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:26.479
So it was nice to put it in its own page

00:16:26.479 --> 00:16:29.760
where it could just flag to users, this is an activity.

00:16:29.760 --> 00:16:30.760
And then we could even flag

00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:32.679
some of these functions to show them

00:16:32.679 --> 00:16:34.059
these are different types of places

00:16:34.059 --> 00:16:35.400
you might end up doing it.

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:40.520
Another interesting one is this formatting pattern

00:16:40.520 --> 00:16:44.400
that there's these parameters USEPs and locale.

00:16:44.400 --> 00:16:47.239
And locale, I've actually never said that word out loud.

00:16:47.239 --> 00:16:49.719
But I've thought it a lot.

00:16:49.719 --> 00:16:54.719
So locale is shared by most of the format functions.

00:16:56.520 --> 00:16:59.200
And another interesting thing is it interacts sometimes

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:01.159
with different parameters.

00:17:01.159 --> 00:17:03.500
So to show you how locale might work,

00:17:04.439 --> 00:17:07.599
if you have say like the English number,

00:17:07.599 --> 00:17:09.040
well, this is just a number.

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:12.599
But 1,234, you know, in English,

00:17:12.599 --> 00:17:16.119
you might separate the one into a comma, it's a unit.

00:17:16.119 --> 00:17:18.199
In German, you might use a period.

00:17:19.599 --> 00:17:23.319
But then you might use a comma where the English period was.

00:17:23.319 --> 00:17:26.160
And if you use NOCEPS, you might not have a comma at all.

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:28.319
So essentially locale determines

00:17:28.319 --> 00:17:30.280
how these numbers get formatted,

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:33.280
and it interacts with other things.

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:35.119
So in this case, sometimes it's really useful

00:17:35.119 --> 00:17:37.479
to flag these dynamics.

00:17:37.479 --> 00:17:39.199
A user clicking through your reference

00:17:39.199 --> 00:17:42.239
is just gonna hit this definition over and over.

00:17:42.239 --> 00:17:44.599
So our docs would just tell you what a locale is

00:17:44.599 --> 00:17:46.239
over and over and over.

00:17:46.239 --> 00:17:48.560
But we can have one page that actually surfaces

00:17:48.560 --> 00:17:51.719
this dynamic across a bunch of different things

00:17:51.719 --> 00:17:53.640
and shows you where it comes up.

00:17:54.479 --> 00:17:56.260
All right, so I'm gonna go quickly

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:59.479
on the very last workshop piece.

00:17:59.479 --> 00:18:02.880
This is all to say, for the user guide,

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:04.760
we usually break it down by topic.

00:18:04.760 --> 00:18:06.400
I'm gonna scooch so fast.

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:09.199
For the workshop, we go by case study.

00:18:09.199 --> 00:18:12.520
And the case studies usually are able to link to the guide.

00:18:12.520 --> 00:18:14.540
But this has been really helpful for us

00:18:14.540 --> 00:18:17.000
because people can graze the user guide.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.599
But then the case studies we use to kind of say,

00:18:19.599 --> 00:18:22.079
what's the slice across topics you need

00:18:22.079 --> 00:18:25.160
to do the next most interesting thing?

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:29.560
All right, so that's the whole idea of the five steps.

00:18:29.560 --> 00:18:31.000
Thanks you so much for watching.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.599
If you find any cursed docs, please send them to me.

00:18:33.599 --> 00:18:35.400
I'm an avid collector.

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:38.040
And thanks so much for watching.

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:43.040
Okay, thank you.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:48.719
We have time for one question.

00:18:48.719 --> 00:18:53.719
So how much documentation is too much documentation?

00:18:55.920 --> 00:18:57.439
I don't know.

00:18:57.439 --> 00:19:00.040
I don't even think I should document an answer to that.

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:02.560
But I don't think you can have too much.

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:07.359
But I do think the odds of it becoming cursed grows

00:19:07.359 --> 00:19:09.239
the more documentation you have.

00:19:09.239 --> 00:19:12.400
Okay, actually I have time for one more

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:13.640
if you're good with that.

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:19.459
Do GT and Pointblank use the Cordodox package?

00:19:19.459 --> 00:19:23.239
If yes, will it replace Packagedown for R in the future?

00:19:23.239 --> 00:19:24.060
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:19:24.060 --> 00:19:26.400
I'm the maintainer of this package called Cordodox

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:29.000
to create an API reference in Python.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.880
So GreatTables and Pointblank do use it.

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:33.680
But Packagedown's all R packages.

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:35.839
So I don't think it's gonna replace

00:19:35.839 --> 00:19:36.920
Packagedown anytime soon.

00:19:36.920 --> 00:19:38.800
As a Python developer, I don't have,

00:19:38.800 --> 00:19:41.400
I love R, I actually absolutely love R and use it.

00:19:41.400 --> 00:19:42.400
But I don't have room in my heart

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:45.359
to think about stepping on Hadley's territory.

00:19:45.359 --> 00:19:48.160
I feel like he's pretty set, you know?

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:49.400
Yeah.

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:50.239
Okay, great.

00:19:50.239 --> 00:19:52.719
Thank you and let's thank all of the speakers

00:19:52.719 --> 00:19:53.699
for today's session.

00:19:53.699 --> 00:19:54.540
All right.

00:19:54.540 --> 00:19:55.359
Thank you.

